Data Analysis Project

The Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) - 2013

Background

The Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) is a collaborative project between all of the states in the United States (US) and participating US territories and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). The BRFSS is administered and supported by CDCs Population Health Surveillance Branch, under the Division of Population Health at the National Center for Chronic Disease Prevention and Health Promotion. BRFSS is an ongoing surveillance system designed to measure behavioral risk factors for the non-institutionalized adult population (18 years of age and older) residing in the US. The BRFSS was initiated in 1984, with 15 states collecting surveillance data on risk behaviors through monthly telephone interviews. Over time, the number of states participating in the survey increased; by 2001, 50 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, Guam, and the US Virgin Islands were participating in the BRFSS. Today, all 50 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and Guam collect data annually and American Samoa, Federated States of Micronesia, and Palau collect survey data over a limited point- in-time (usually one to three months). In this document, the term state is used to refer to all areas participating in BRFSS, including the District of Columbia, Guam, and the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico.

The BRFSS objective is to collect uniform, state-specific data on preventive health practices and risk behaviors that are linked to chronic diseases, injuries, and preventable infectious diseases that affect the adult population. Factors assessed by the BRFSS in 2013 include tobacco use, HIV/AIDS knowledge and prevention, exercise, immunization, health status, healthy days health-related quality of life, health care access, inadequate sleep, hypertension awareness, cholesterol awareness, chronic health conditions, alcohol consumption, fruits and vegetables consumption, arthritis burden, and seatbelt use. Since 2011, BRFSS conducts both landline telephone- and cellular telephone-based surveys. In conducting the BRFSS landline telephone survey, interviewers collect data from a randomly selected adult in a household. In conducting the cellular telephone version of the BRFSS questionnaire, interviewers collect data from an adult who participates by using a cellular telephone and resides in a private residence or college housing.

Health characteristics estimated from the BRFSS pertain to the non-institutionalized adult population, aged 18 years or older, who reside in the US. In 2013, additional question sets were included as optional modules to provide a measure for several childhood health and wellness indicators, including asthma prevalence for people aged 17 years or younger.

Part 2: Research questions

To identify the health care coverage across all states

In this section we will identify the coverage of each states and compares the coverage among other states. This will shows the differences of coverage among each states and identified which states have the higher coverage and which states have the lowest coverage.

To identify the relationship between the income level and health care coverage

The income level is identified by the following levels:-
  1. Less than $10,000
  2. Less than $15,000
  3. Less than $20,000
  4. Less than $25,000
  5. Less than $35,000
  6. Less than $50,000
  7. Less than $75,000
  8. $75,000 or more

In this section we will identify if the level of income affected the health care coverage.

To identify the relationship between income level and general health condition

The general health condition in the dataset is categorized as follows:-
  1. Excellent
  2. Very good
  3. Good
  4. Fair
  5. Poor

In this section we will identify if the general health condition and level of income is affected each others.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

To identify the different of health care accessibility across all states

We know from previous analysis shows the dataset contains 491,775 rows, the datasets need to be cleaned and removed from unnecessary items such as NA values. The following shows the dataset column X_state after removed the NA values.

sum(is.na(brfss2013$X_state))
## [1] 0

The above shows that X-state column does not have any NA values.

The following shows the NA values for dataset column hlthpln1.

sum(is.na(brfss2013$hlthpln1))
## [1] 1904

Prior to proceed further in the analysis, we need to identify the accuracy of the analysis after removing the NA value.

The following shows that the NA values only consist of 0.3% from the overall dataset values. Therefore the estimated accuracy of the analysis is 99.7%.

(sum(is.na(brfss2013$hlthpln1)) / length(brfss2013$hlthpln1)) * 100
## [1] 0.3871689

The following shows the dataset after removing the NA values. Additional column thats shows the non health coverage, total health coverage and the ratio of the health coverage is included in the dataset prior plotting the graph.

states <- brfss2013 %>%
    select(X_state, hlthpln1) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    group_by(X_state) %>%
    summarise(hlth = sum(hlthpln1 == "Yes", na.rm = T), nohlth = sum(hlthpln1 == "No", na.rm = T)) %>%
        mutate(total = hlth + nohlth) %>%
    mutate(ratio = hlth / (hlth + nohlth)) %>%
    arrange(desc(ratio))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
head(states)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##   X_state               hlth nohlth total ratio
##   <fct>                <int>  <int> <int> <dbl>
## 1 Massachusetts        14377    642 15019 0.957
## 2 District of Columbia  4698    220  4918 0.955
## 3 Puerto Rico           5708    286  5994 0.952
## 4 Iowa                  7606    527  8133 0.935
## 5 Vermont               5949    427  6376 0.933
## 6 Maryland             12064    904 12968 0.930
nrow(states)
## [1] 53
ggplot(states, aes(X_state, ratio, fill = X_state)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    xlab("States") +
    ylab("Health Care Coverage Ratio") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
    ggtitle("Health Care Coverage by All States")

Based on the above graph shows that most of the states have coverage more than 0.75. Therefore, we set a health coverage threshold at 0.8, in order to identify which states have a lower health coverage.

below <- states %>%
    filter(ratio < 0.8)
nrow(below)
## [1] 2
ggplot(below, aes(X_state, ratio, fill = X_state)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    xlab("States") +
    ylab("Health Care Coverage Ratio") +
    ggtitle("Health Care Coverage Below 0.8")

Based on the above graph shows that from 53 states, 2 states with health coverage below 0.8, which are Texas and Guam.

above <- states %>%
    filter(ratio > 0.9)
nrow(above)
## [1] 20
ggplot(above, aes(X_state, ratio, fill = X_state)) + 
        geom_bar(stat = "identity") + xlab("States") + 
        ylab("Health Care Coverage Ratio") + 
        theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + 
        ggtitle("Health Care Coverage Above 0.9")

Based on the above graph shows that there are 20 states out from 53 states that have health coverage more than 0.9. This also shows that there are 31 states that have health coverage between 0.8 and 0.9.

income_hlth <- brfss2013 %>%
  select(income2, hlthpln1) %>%
  na.omit()

ggplot(income_hlth, aes(income2, fill = hlthpln1)) + geom_bar() +
     xlab("Income Level") +
    ylab("") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
    ggtitle("Health Care Coverage by Income Level")

Based on the above graph shows that higher income level have more health care coverage.

genplot <- brfss2013 %>%
  select(income2, genhlth) %>%
  na.omit()

ggplot(genplot, aes(income2, fill = genhlth)) + geom_bar() + xlab("Income Level") + ylab("") + 
theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
ggtitle("General Health Condition by Income Level")

Based on the above graph shows that higher income level have more excellent and very good level of general health condition. While for lower income level tend to have less excellent and very good level of general health condition.

Summary

To identify the health care coverage across all states:-

  1. The dataset consist of NA value of 0.3% from overall. Therefore, the estimated accuracy of the analysis is 99.7%
  2. The analysis shows that from 53 states, 2 states with health coverage below 0.8, which are Texas and Guam
  3. The analysis shows that there are 20 states out from 53 states that have health coverage more than 0.9
  4. The analysis shows that there are 31 states that have health coverage between 0.8 and 0.9

To identify the relationship between the income level and health care coverage

  1. The dataset consist of NA value of 14.5% from overall dataset values. Therefore, the estimated accuracy of the analysis is 85.5%
  2. The analysis shows that higher income level have more health care coverage

To identify the relationship between income level and general health condition

  1. The dataset consist of NA values of 0.4% from overall dataset values. Therefore, the estimated accuracy of the analysis is 99.6%
  2. The analysis shows that higher income level have more excellent and very good level of general health condition
  3. While for lower income level tend to have less excellent and very good level of general health condition
